      <hedline>
        <hl1>The China Debate</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Thomas P Bernstein letter on James P Hoffa's May 11 article favors permanent normal trade ties to China</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>James P. Hoffa's May 11 Op-Ed article is mistaken in its assumption that trade sanctions against China lead to improvements in religious freedom or labor conditions. Every year for two decades, Congress has debated most favored nation status for China and has often sought to link renewal to human rights, but there is no evidence that these debates have had any concrete effect.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>James P. Hoffa's May 11 Op-Ed article is mistaken in its assumption that trade sanctions against China lead to improvements in religious freedom or labor conditions. Every year for two decades, Congress has debated most favored nation status for China and has often sought to link renewal to human rights, but there is no evidence that these debates have had any concrete effect.</p>
        <p>Turning down permanent normal trade relations with China will not provide additional leverage. Instead, it will cause a major anti-American backlash in China. Political, economic and social conditions in China will improve as the country develops, as China becomes more integrated into the international community, and as the influence of international norms gains ground.</p>
        <p>Voting against permanent normal trade relations is China-bashing. The impulse should be resisted.</p>
        <p>THOMAS P. BERNSTEIN  New York, May 12, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor in the East Asian Institute, Columbia University.</p>
      </block>
